1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
Are you looking to configure your home page display and how posts will appear?

2
00:00:05,120 --> 00:00:08,120
Well, let's go to Reading Settings.

3
00:00:08,640 --> 00:00:11,640
When you're in the dashboard, make your way to Settings and then click on Reading.

4
00:00:14,120 --> 00:00:17,120
The Your Home Page Displays section located at the top is an important part of setting

5
00:00:19,160 --> 00:00:22,160
up your site's front page.

6
00:00:21,280 --> 00:00:24,280
It allows you to choose between a feed of your most recent blog posts or an existing

7
00:00:25,960 --> 00:00:28,960
static page.

8
00:00:27,520 --> 00:00:30,520
If you opt for your latest posts, your front page will be a chronological list of your

9
00:00:32,240 --> 00:00:35,240
most recent blog posts.

10
00:00:34,840 --> 00:00:37,840
It's important to note that if you choose your latest posts as your home page display, you

11
00:00:39,360 --> 00:00:42,360
will need to build your home page within the blog home template, depending on your theme.

12
00:00:45,320 --> 00:00:48,320
Let's see this in action by going to the Site Editor.

13
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:55,000
If we click on Pages, we will see at the top next to the Home icon, our home page is our

14
00:00:57,760 --> 00:01:00,760
Blog Home Template.

15
00:00:59,640 --> 00:01:02,640
And when we open up our Blog Home Template, we will see our latest posts.

16
00:01:04,720 --> 00:01:07,720
And as mentioned, this is the place we will edit our home page if we select latest posts

17
00:01:09,840 --> 00:01:12,840
as our home page display.

18
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:16,280
For my business website, I've chosen to set a static home page.

19
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:20,000
I will go to the drop down and the home page and then select the home page I already created.

20
00:01:23,520 --> 00:01:26,520
I also created a news page and will set that as my static posts page.

21
00:01:28,520 --> 00:01:31,520
If you don't want a blog or posts page on your site, you can just skip this step.

22
00:01:33,680 --> 00:01:36,680
Keep in mind that if you choose this option, your home page will be assigned to the pages

23
00:01:38,200 --> 00:01:41,200
template by default and your posts page will be assigned to the blog home template.

24
00:01:43,880 --> 00:01:46,880
We can see how this works when we make our way to Pages and open up our home page.

25
00:01:52,240 --> 00:01:55,240
And in our sidebar settings, we will see that the home page has been assigned to the pages

26
00:01:56,280 --> 00:01:59,280
template.

27
00:01:57,920 --> 00:02:00,920
And if we make our way to our news page or our posts page, we will see that this page

28
00:02:03,920 --> 00:02:06,920
has been assigned to the blog home template and we will edit this page within the blog

29
00:02:08,440 --> 00:02:11,440
home template.

30
00:02:10,280 --> 00:02:13,280
Something else to mention, when you build your header, remember to add the Home Link block

31
00:02:15,480 --> 00:02:18,480
as your home navigation item.

32
00:02:20,240 --> 00:02:23,240
This link will always direct visitors to your home page regardless of which home page display

33
00:02:25,360 --> 00:02:28,360
setting you selected.

34
00:02:28,640 --> 00:02:31,640
The next section determines how many blog posts are shown before requiring users to click

35
00:02:33,520 --> 00:02:36,520
over to a new page.

36
00:02:35,120 --> 00:02:38,120
I suggest leaving the number at 10 as you don't want to negatively impact your site's

37
00:02:39,440 --> 00:02:42,440
loading time.

38
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:44,200
Please note that you can also change this number when you edit the Query Loop block

39
00:02:45,200 --> 00:02:48,200
displaying your posts.

40
00:02:47,600 --> 00:02:50,600
This next setting controls how many of your websites posts are shown in the RSS feed.

41
00:02:53,720 --> 00:02:56,720
The RSS feed is a way for users to subscribe to your website and receive updates whenever

42
00:03:00,080 --> 00:03:03,080
you publish new content.

43
00:03:02,560 --> 00:03:05,560
Think of it like a notification system that keeps readers informed about your latest posts.

44
00:03:09,680 --> 00:03:12,680
When you add new content to your site, the RSS feed automatically updates to include

45
00:03:14,760 --> 00:03:17,760
the new posts.

46
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:19,440
By adjusting this setting, you can decide how many of these posts will be visible in

47
00:03:20,680 --> 00:03:23,680
the feed at any given time.

48
00:03:23,080 --> 00:03:26,080
You can set this to any amount that suits your needs but I will keep it at 10.

49
00:03:28,240 --> 00:03:31,240
I can also specify whether the feed will include a summary or the full content of the post.

50
00:03:33,920 --> 00:03:36,920
I am going to switch this over to Summary or Excerpt which will show any catchy excerpt

51
00:03:39,880 --> 00:03:42,880
I wrote in the meta box when I created my post.

52
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:46,400
Lastly, we have an option called Search Engine Visibility.

53
00:03:47,960 --> 00:03:50,960
I recommend checking this box only if your website is in the development phase.

54
00:03:52,440 --> 00:03:55,440
It will minimize the chances of it being picked up.

55
00:03:55,480 --> 00:03:58,480
But don't forget to uncheck it when your site goes into production as you will want

56
00:03:59,560 --> 00:04:02,560
search engines to index your site.

